1. Generate a New GitHub Personal Access Token
Login to GitHub:

Go to GitHub.com and log in to your account.
Navigate to Settings:

Click on your profile picture in the upper-right corner.
Select "Settings" from the dropdown menu.
Go to Developer Settings:

In the left sidebar, scroll down and click on "Developer settings."
Personal Access Tokens:

Click on "Personal access tokens" in the left sidebar, then click on "Tokens (classic)".
Click on "Generate new token" (or "Generate new token (classic)" if it's listed).
Select Scopes:

Give the token a descriptive name.
Select the scopes or permissions you need. For example, to push to repositories, you'll need to select the repo scope.
Generate the Token:

Click on the "Generate token" button.
Copy the token immediately as you wonâ€™t be able to view it again.


git config --global --get credential.helper
git config --global --unset credential.helper
rm ~/.git-credentials
git credential-manager erase
git remote -v
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/TechHunter07/k8.git
git config --global credential.helper store
git push origin main


